with my knowledge.

00:14:04.059 --> 00:14:06.059
If I call set input, you can see the app update live.

00:14:07.159 --> 00:14:09.159
It didn't have to do anything, you didn't have to refresh.

00:14:10.260 --> 00:14:12.260
When we clicked read, it actually updated live, you can see the

00:14:12.260 --> 00:14:14.260
output there.

00:14:15.559 --> 00:14:17.559
I think that is just so powerful, because you can be, like,

00:14:17.559 --> 00:14:19.559
why is this test not working?

00:14:20.859 --> 00:14:22.859
Run, run, run, run, insert app dollar view in the console, and

00:14:22.859 --> 00:14:24.859
you can see exactly where it's at.

00:14:26.059 --> 00:14:28.059
And you know your app, and you'll be able to discover what's

00:14:28.059 --> 00:14:30.059
wrong, whereas shiny test 2 can only tell you what's going on.

00:14:34.559 --> 00:14:36.559
So, I have some suggestions as you

00:14:37.659 --> 00:14:39.659
leave the shiny Shire, and your way to test.

00:14:43.659 --> 00:14:45.659
Number one is to use shiny export test values.

00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:48.760
This is a method that I was actually unaware of, and I'm on

00:14:48.760 --> 00:14:50.760
the shiny team, and I really want to give it more limelight,

00:14:52.760 --> 00:14:54.760
because it is very powerful.

00:14:56.059 --> 00:14:58.059
We don't need to test just input and output, there's actually a

00:14:58.059 --> 00:15:00.059
third group called export.

00:15:01.359 --> 00:15:03.359
And you can export React values, you can export using

00:15:03.859 --> 00:15:05.859
React, and you can export your React value, and it doesn't need

00:15:05.859 --> 00:15:07.859
to be an input or something that has been rendered as an output.

00:15:10.460 --> 00:15:12.460
And this is great, because testing mode will allow for this

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:16.460
to work, and you can expose more information and more work logic

00:15:16.460 --> 00:15:18.460
that doesn't be in your normal app that you use day-to-day.

00:15:21.960 --> 00:15:23.960
Also, try to limit objects under your own control.

00:15:26.260 --> 00:15:28.260
If you do something like data structure, and then you send it

00:15:28.260 --> 00:15:31.260
into DT, and DT updates because it needs to, like, nothing

00:15:31.260 --> 00:15:33.260
wrong with that.

00:15:34.359 --> 00:15:36.359
It's not going to do anything wrong with DT doing that, but

00:15:36.359 --> 00:15:38.359
your output might change, which would produce false positives.

00:15:41.359 --> 00:15:43.359
So maybe just test your data frame going in, and then just

00:15:43.359 --> 00:15:45.359
trust that DT will always run.

00:15:50.359 --> 00:15:52.359
Another one is, again, if you use expect snapshot file, be

00:15:52.359 --> 00:15:54.359
careful about what's going on with those snapshots.

00:15:57.359 --> 00:15:59.359
All the snapshot does is says I agree with myself, but it

00:15:59.359 --> 00:16:01.359
doesn't mean that it's correct.

00:16:03.359 --> 00:16:05.359
If you do agree with yourself, you are correct, so that's good,

00:16:05.359 --> 00:16:07.359
but there's that little logical loophole.

00:16:09.359 --> 00:16:11.359
Be safe, you can always use manual expectations or explicit

00:16:11.359 --> 00:16:13.359
expectations, such as expect equal, because that will always

00:16:13.359 --> 00:16:15.359
be truthful if you're comparing it to a static.

00:16:19.359 --> 00:16:21.359
And then, lastly, minimize the number of screenshot

00:16:21.359 --> 00:16:23.359
expectations.

00:16:25.359 --> 00:16:27.359
Screenshots are worth a thousand tests.

00:16:27.359 --> 00:16:29.359
They do test everything, but you can also imagine that's a very

00:16:29.359 --> 00:16:31.359
high fallback.

00:16:33.359 --> 00:16:35.359
They're very brittle, they're open to a lot of issues, and

00:16:35.359 --> 00:16:37.359
also you cannot compare across operating systems or R versions,

00:16:37.359 --> 00:16:39.359
so it gets very unwieldy very quickly.

00:16:43.359 --> 00:16:45.359
So unless screenshots are absolute, I would argue maybe

00:16:45.359 --> 00:16:47.359
not do that.

